<p><b>Coolhunting</b> is a term coined in the early 1990s referring to a new breed of <a href="/wiki/Marketing" title="Marketing">marketing</a> professionals, called <b>coolhunters</b>. It is their job to make <a href="/wiki/Observation" title="Observation">observations</a> and <a href="/wiki/Prediction" title="Prediction">predictions</a> in changes of new or existing cultural <a href="/wiki/Trend" title="Trend">trends</a>. The word derives from the <a href="/wiki/Cool_(aesthetic)" title="Cool (aesthetic)">aesthetic of "cool"</a>.</p>
<p>In this they resemble the <a href="/wiki/Intuition_(knowledge)" title="Intuition (knowledge)">intuitive</a> fashion magazine editors of the 1960s such as <a href="/w/index.php?title=Nancy_White_(editor)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Nancy White (editor) (page does not exist)">Nancy White</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Harper%27s_Bazaar" title="Harper's Bazaar">Harper's Bazaar</a></i> 1958-1971). Coolhunters operate most notably in the world of <a href="/wiki/Street_fashion" title="Street fashion">street fashion</a> and design, but their work also blurs into that of <a href="/wiki/Futurology" title="Futurology">futurists</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Faith_Popcorn" title="Faith Popcorn">Faith Popcorn</a>. Many <a href="/wiki/Weblogger" title="Weblogger" class="mw-redirect">webloggers</a> now serve as online coolhunters, in a variety of cultural and technological areas.</p>
<p><i><a href="/wiki/Pattern_Recognition_(novel)" title="Pattern Recognition (novel)">Pattern Recognition</a></i>, a 2003 novel by <a href="/wiki/William_Gibson" title="William Gibson">William Gibson</a>, features a coolhunter as its main character.</p>
